To carry out our experiment, 0.9 mL of concentrated microalgal inoculum (106 cells mL−1, determined by OD670 measurement) were transferred to each flask, containing 90 mL of every dilution of the compound. Thus, the initial concentration of microalgae in each flask was 104 cells mL−1. Such sufficiently low initial concentration eliminates the risk of nutrient depletion. Potentially toxic concentrations varied from 0.01 mg L−1 to 100 mg L−1, with the individual dilution factor (IDF) q = 10. Then, 25 mL of the microalgae-toxicant dilutions from each flask were transferred into test vials and incubated at 23 ± 2 °C with sideways illumination of 10,000 lx for three days, under a photoperiod of 24 h of light for 0 h of darkness (24/0; L/D). The microalgal culture without noncompound was used as a negative control sample. After every 24 h, OD670 was measured, and the specific growth rates (µ) for each test and control batch replicate were calculated from the Eq. (1):1μ=lnnL-lnn0tL-t0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
